A1: Kristján Eldjárn was a teacher at the Akureyri Grammar School and the College of Navigation in Reykjavík before he became president.

Q2: How did Kristján Eldjárn become popular?
A2: Kristján Eldjárn hosted a series of educational TV programs on the Icelandic National Television (RÚV) in 1966-1968, where he showed the audience some of the National Museum's artefacts and explained their historical context. These programs became quite popular, making him a well-known and respected popular figure.

Q3: What was the result of the 1968 presidential election?
A3: Kristján Eldjárn won 65.6% of the vote on a 92.2% voter turnout in the 1968 presidential election.

Q4: Did Kristján Eldjárn run for re-election after his first term?
A4: Yes, Kristján Eldjárn was re-elected unopposed in 1972 and 1976.

Q5: What did Kristján Eldjárn decide not to do in 1980?
A5: Kristján Eldjárn decided not to run for another term as president in 1980, wanting to devote his remaining years entirely to continuing his lifelong academic work.

Q6: What happened to Kristján Eldjárn after heart surgery?
A6: Kristján Eldjárn died following heart surgery in Cleveland, Ohio on September 13, 1982.

Q7: Are there any notable descendants of Kristján Eldjárn?
A7: Yes, Kristján Eldjárn's son Þórarinn Eldjárn is one of Iceland's most popular authors, specializing in short stories, but also writing poetry and an occasional novel. His daughter Sigrún Eldjárn is also an author and illustrator of several children's books. Þórarinn's son, Ari Eldjárn, is Iceland's most prominent stand-up comedian.
